00:04:39.750 --> 00:04:42.970
I'm excited to read to you from
Last Stop on Market Street.

00:04:48.350 --> 00:04:53.580
C.J. pushed through the church
doors, skipped down the steps.

00:04:53.580 --> 00:04:57.770
The outside air smelled like
freedom, but it also smelled

00:04:57.770 --> 00:05:04.300
like rain, which freckled C.J.
shirt and dripped down his nose.

00:05:06.010 --> 00:05:09.620
He ducked under his
nana's umbrella saying,

00:05:09.620 --> 00:05:13.840
"How come we got to wait for
the bus in all this wet?"

00:05:13.840 --> 00:05:16.730
"Trees get thirsty,
too," his nana told him.

00:05:16.730 --> 00:05:20.330
"Don't you see that big one
drinking through a straw?"

00:05:20.330 --> 00:05:24.200
C.J. looked for a long
time but never saw a straw.

00:05:24.200 --> 00:05:27.380
And by the way, if you, little
guys, if you can see the straw

00:05:27.380 --> 00:05:29.520
that that tree is drinking from,

00:05:29.520 --> 00:05:31.630
then you understand
the entire book.

00:05:31.630 --> 00:05:38.000
But we won't get into that now.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:42.610
From the bus stop, he watched
water pool on flower petals,

00:05:42.610 --> 00:05:47.180
watched rain patter against
the windshield of a nearby car.

00:05:47.180 --> 00:05:50.760
His friend Colby climbed
in, gave C.J. a wave,

00:05:50.760 --> 00:05:53.680
and drove off with his dad.

00:05:53.680 --> 00:05:56.950
"Nana, how come we
don't got a car?"

00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:03.880
"Boy, what do we need a car for?

00:06:03.880 --> 00:06:07.030
We got a bus that breathes
fire, and old Mr. Dennis

00:06:07.030 --> 00:06:10.160
who always has a trick for you."

00:06:10.160 --> 00:06:13.240
The bus creaked to a
stop in front of them.

00:06:13.240 --> 00:06:20.340
It sighed and sagged and
the doors swung open.

00:06:20.340 --> 00:06:21.670
"What's that I see?"

00:06:21.670 --> 00:06:24.070
Mr. Dennis asked.

00:06:24.070 --> 00:06:27.130
He pulled a coin from
behind C.J.'s ear,

00:06:27.130 --> 00:06:29.490
placed it in his palm.

00:06:29.490 --> 00:06:33.970
Nana laughed her deep laugh
and pushed C.J. along.

00:06:35.350 --> 00:06:37.900
They sat right up
front, which, by the way,

00:06:37.900 --> 00:06:39.700
is one of the most
important lines in the book

00:06:39.700 --> 00:06:42.520
and nobody really
talks about it.

00:06:42.520 --> 00:06:45.640
The man across the way
was tuning a guitar.

00:06:45.640 --> 00:06:50.200
An old woman with curlers
had butterflies in a jar.

00:06:50.200 --> 00:06:55.240
Nana gave everyone a great big
smile and a good afternoon.

00:06:55.240 --> 00:07:00.830
She made sure C.J. did the same.

00:07:00.830 --> 00:07:04.040
The bus lurched forward
and stopped,

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:05.880
lurched forward and stopped.

00:07:05.880 --> 00:07:08.060
Nana hummed as she knit.

00:07:08.060 --> 00:07:11.500
"How come we always got
to go here after church?"

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:12.800
C.J. said.

00:07:12.800 --> 00:07:16.360
"Miguel and Colby never
have to go nowhere."

00:07:16.360 --> 00:07:18.750
"I feel sorry for those
boys," she told him.

00:07:18.750 --> 00:07:23.600
"They'll never get a chance to
meet Bobo or the Sunglass Man,

00:07:23.600 --> 00:07:27.330
and I hear Trixie got
herself a brand-new hat."

00:07:27.330 --> 00:07:31.510
C.J. stared out the window
feeling sorry for himself.

00:07:31.510 --> 00:07:35.560
He watched cars zip by on
either side, watched a group

00:07:35.560 --> 00:07:39.520
of boys hop curbs on bikes.

00:07:39.520 --> 00:07:45.300
A man climbed aboard
with a spotted dog.

00:07:45.300 --> 00:07:47.650
C.J. gave up his seat.

00:07:47.650 --> 00:07:51.380
"How come that man can't see?"

00:07:51.380 --> 00:07:52.970
"Boy, what do you
know about seeing?"

00:07:52.970 --> 00:07:54.390
his nana told him.

00:07:54.390 --> 00:07:58.150
"Some people watch the
world with their ears."

00:07:58.150 --> 00:07:59.520
"That's a fact.

00:07:59.520 --> 00:08:01.980
Their noses, too," the man
said, sniffing at the air.

00:08:01.980 --> 00:08:05.580
"That's a mighty fine perfume
you're wearing today, ma'am."

00:08:05.580 --> 00:08:10.460
Nana squeezed the man's hand
and laughed her deep laugh.

00:08:13.030 --> 00:08:15.430
Two older boys got on next.

00:08:15.430 --> 00:08:20.870
C.J. watched as they moved
on by and stood in back.

00:08:20.870 --> 00:08:22.700
"Sure wish I had one
of those," he said.

00:08:22.700 --> 00:08:24.500
And if you can't
see in the back,

00:08:24.500 --> 00:08:26.210
they're listening to headphones.

00:08:26.210 --> 00:08:30.710
They probably have
an iPhone or iPod.

00:08:30.710 --> 00:08:32.280
Nana set down her knitting.

00:08:32.280 --> 00:08:34.890
And by the way, if your
grandmother ever sets

00:08:34.890 --> 00:08:36.910
down her knitting, you know
you might be in trouble.

00:08:36.910 --> 00:08:38.790
[laughter].

00:08:38.790 --> 00:08:40.090
"What for?

00:08:40.090 --> 00:08:43.070
You got the real-life thing
sitting across from you.

00:08:43.070 --> 00:08:46.520
Why don't you ask the man
if he'll play us a song?"

00:08:46.520 --> 00:08:48.110
C.J. didn't have to.

00:08:48.110 --> 00:08:50.750
The guitar player was
already plucking strings

00:08:50.750 --> 00:08:52.910
and beginning to sing.

00:08:52.910 --> 00:08:56.410
"To feel the magic of music,"
the blind man whispered,

00:08:56.410 --> 00:08:58.750
"I like to close my eyes."

00:08:58.750 --> 00:09:01.100
Nana closed hers, too.

00:09:01.100 --> 00:09:04.860
So did C.J. and the spotted dog.

00:09:04.860 --> 00:09:10.860
And in the darkness,
the rhythm lifted C.J.

00:09:10.860 --> 00:09:14.250
out of the bus, out
of the busy city.

00:09:14.250 --> 00:09:18.530
He saw sunset colors
swirling over crashing waves,

00:09:18.530 --> 00:09:22.010
saw a family of hawks
slicing through the sky,

00:09:22.010 --> 00:09:25.120
saw the old woman's
butterflies dancing free

00:09:25.120 --> 00:09:27.320
in the light of the moon.

00:09:27.320 --> 00:09:31.620
C.J.'s chest grew full and
he was lost in the sound,

00:09:31.620 --> 00:09:36.140
and the sound gave him
the feeling of magic.

00:09:37.330 --> 00:09:41.010
The song ended and
C.J. opened his eyes.

00:09:41.010 --> 00:09:45.480
Everyone on the bus clapped,
even the boys in back.

00:09:45.480 --> 00:09:49.580
Nana glanced at the
coin in C.J.'s palm.

00:09:49.580 --> 00:09:53.450
C.J. dropped it in
the man's hat.

00:09:53.450 --> 00:09:56.970
"Last stop on Market
Street," Mr. Dennis called.

00:10:01.820 --> 00:10:05.590
C.J. looked around as
he stepped off the bus.

00:10:05.590 --> 00:10:09.070
Crumbling sidewalks
and broken-down doors,

00:10:09.070 --> 00:10:12.080
graffiti-tagged windows
and boarded-up stores.

00:10:12.080 --> 00:10:14.990
He reached for his nana's hands.

00:10:14.990 --> 00:10:18.780
"How come it's always
so dirty over here?"

00:10:18.780 --> 00:10:22.290
She smiled and pointed
to the sky.

00:10:22.290 --> 00:10:25.920
"Sometimes when you're
surrounded by dirt, C.J.,

00:10:25.920 --> 00:10:28.900
you're a better witness
for what's beautiful."

00:10:31.250 --> 00:10:35.680
C.J. saw the perfect rainbow
arcing over their soup kitchen.

00:10:35.680 --> 00:10:38.600
He wondered how his nana
always found beautiful

00:10:38.600 --> 00:10:40.820
where he never even
thought to look.

00:10:40.820 --> 00:10:44.860
He looked all around them again,
at the bus rounding the corner

00:10:44.860 --> 00:10:49.720
out of sight and the broken
street lamps still lit up right

00:10:49.720 --> 00:10:53.790
and the stray cat shadows
moving across the wall.

00:10:55.710 --> 00:10:58.210
When he spotted their
familiar faces in the window,

00:10:58.210 --> 00:11:00.510
he said, "I'm glad we came."

00:11:06.590 --> 00:11:10.470
He thought his nana might laugh
her deep laugh, but she didn't.

00:11:10.470 --> 00:11:13.690
She patted him on the
head and told him, "Me,

00:11:13.690 --> 00:11:15.780
too, C.J. Now come on."

00:11:15.780 --> 00:11:19.860
And the last page you see
C.J. and his grandmother,

00:11:19.860 --> 00:11:22.930
they're at the soup kitchen,
but they're not there to eat.

00:11:22.930 --> 00:11:24.230
They're there to serve.

00:11:24.230 --> 00:11:26.510
Thank you guys so much for
letting me read to you.

00:11:26.510 --> 00:11:34.800
[ Applause ]

00:11:34.800 --> 00:11:36.100
&gt;&gt; Caroline Quandt: Wonderful.

00:11:36.100 --> 00:11:37.400
Thank you, Matt.

00:11:37.400 --> 00:11:41.550
What a wonderful book about
community and finding value

00:11:41.550 --> 00:11:44.810
in the little things in
life and in giving, yes?

